1
00:00:01,150 --> 00:00:05,170
If you look at any price chart and you will
notice that price does not move in a straight

2
00:00:05,170 --> 00:00:06,170
line.

3
00:00:06,170 --> 00:00:08,040
It does not move up or down vertically.

4
00:00:08,040 --> 00:00:11,780
It moves in waves, and these waves are called
market swings.

5
00:00:11,780 --> 00:00:16,250
In a bull market, price rises with a series
of up and downswings.

6
00:00:16,250 --> 00:00:20,539
Naturally, the upswings generally exceed the
downswings in length.

7
00:00:20,539 --> 00:00:22,550
The reverse is true in a bear market.

8
00:00:22,550 --> 00:00:27,499
By observing market swings, you will be able
to notice the structure of the market and

9
00:00:27,499 --> 00:00:30,720
get clues on whether the market will move
up or down.

10
00:00:30,720 --> 00:00:36,780
And following market swings must be your first
step to read the market bias.

11
00:00:36,780 --> 00:00:41,820
Another way to look at market swings is to
think of them as a higher time frame perspective.

12
00:00:41,820 --> 00:00:45,190
Each swing is equivalent to a bar in a higher
time frame.

13
00:00:45,190 --> 00:00:49,670
This is why some traders use a higher time
frame to evaluate market bias.

14
00:00:49,670 --> 00:00:52,380
There are two challenges with the higher time
frame approach.

15
00:00:52,380 --> 00:00:56,670
First, the higher time frame is usually chosen
arbitrarily.

16
00:00:56,670 --> 00:00:59,740
Common choices are multiples of three and
five.

17
00:00:59,740 --> 00:01:04,650
For instance, if your trading time frame is
1-minute, using a multiple of five, you will

18
00:01:04,650 --> 00:01:07,970
use the 5-minute chart for determining the
market bias.

19
00:01:07,970 --> 00:01:12,560
However, there is often no sound basis for
the choice of the higher time frame.

20
00:01:12,560 --> 00:01:17,470
Next, by using a higher time frame, you must
split your attention between two time frames.

21
00:01:17,470 --> 00:01:23,490
While some traders might find that manageable,
some try to keep trading as simple as possible

22
00:01:23,490 --> 00:01:25,740
and focus on one chart only.

23
00:01:25,740 --> 00:01:30,979
By analyzing market swings, you will be able
to factor in the price action of a higher

24
00:01:30,979 --> 00:01:35,000
order into your analysis without a second
chart showing a higher time frame.

25
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:39,630
The advantage of this approach is that you
will be able to evaluate the ongoing price

26
00:01:39,630 --> 00:01:42,700
action within its larger context on the same
chart.

27
00:01:42,700 --> 00:01:48,590
So, we will focus on reading market swings
to deduce the market bias using a single time

28
00:01:48,590 --> 00:01:49,590
frame.

29
00:01:49,590 --> 00:01:52,870
So how to define market swings.

30
00:01:52,870 --> 00:01:58,250
The first step is to classify every price
bar into one of the following four types:

31
00:01:58,250 --> 00:02:03,220
up bars, down bars, inside bars and outside
bars.

32
00:02:03,220 --> 00:02:07,960
These labels describe the relationship of
each bar high/low relative to the previous

33
00:02:07,960 --> 00:02:08,960
bar.

34
00:02:08,960 --> 00:02:09,960
1.

35
00:02:09,960 --> 00:02:14,860
Up bars have the following characteristics
– Higher high, higher low compared to the

36
00:02:14,860 --> 00:02:16,719
previous bar
2.

37
00:02:16,719 --> 00:02:20,799
Down bars have lower high, lower low compared
to the previous bar

38
00:02:20,799 --> 00:02:22,069
3.

39
00:02:22,069 --> 00:02:26,170
Inside bars have lower high, higher low relative
to the previous bar

40
00:02:26,170 --> 00:02:32,430
If the high or the low or both are equal to
that of the previous bar, it is still considered

41
00:02:32,430 --> 00:02:33,590
an inside bar.

42
00:02:33,590 --> 00:02:34,590
4.

43
00:02:34,590 --> 00:02:39,099
Outside bars have higher high, lower low relative
to the previous bar

44
00:02:39,099 --> 00:02:44,349
If either the high or the low are equal to
that of the previous bar, it is still an outside

45
00:02:44,349 --> 00:02:45,549
bar.

46
00:02:45,549 --> 00:02:51,719
So, by using this approach, the closing price
of a price bar does not matter in the classification.

47
00:02:51,719 --> 00:02:55,109
An up bar might close lower than it opened.

48
00:02:55,109 --> 00:02:58,060
A down bar might close higher than it opened.

49
00:02:58,060 --> 00:03:02,680
For a bar that closes higher, we will use
the term “bullish bar”.

50
00:03:02,680 --> 00:03:07,260
For a bar that closes lower, we will use the
term “bearish bar”.

51
00:03:07,260 --> 00:03:11,379
Let’s identify the candles in this example.

52
00:03:11,379 --> 00:03:19,680
We have 4 up bars, followed by an inside bar,
another 3 up bars, and another up bar, despite

53
00:03:19,680 --> 00:03:25,569
being a red candle, because the high and low
were higher relative to previous bar… we

54
00:03:25,569 --> 00:03:35,909
then have a down bar, 3 up bars, 2 down bars
and an inside bar, up bar, then outside bar

55
00:03:35,909 --> 00:03:40,680
because the high and the low are equal to
that of the previous bar, so it is still an

56
00:03:40,680 --> 00:03:41,999
outside bar.

57
00:03:41,999 --> 00:03:50,959
Then an up bar, an outside bar, followed by
an inside bar, and another inside bar, 2 down

58
00:03:50,959 --> 00:04:03,189
bars, 4 up bars, inside bar, down bar, an
inside bar, down bar, an inside bar and finally

59
00:04:03,189 --> 00:04:06,379
an outside bar.

60
00:04:06,379 --> 00:04:11,099
With this approach, you don’t need to memorize
tens of candlestick combinations, you just

61
00:04:11,099 --> 00:04:13,139
need this 4 types of candles.

62
00:04:13,139 --> 00:04:18,489
I recommend opening a chart and start reading
candlesticks until it becomes very easy to

63
00:04:18,489 --> 00:04:20,889
determine which type is.

64
00:04:20,889 --> 00:04:27,520
Do this until you will be able to recognize
the type of the candle almost instantly.

65
00:04:27,520 --> 00:04:31,780
Once you have mastered the different bar types,
you will be able to identify market swings

66
00:04:31,780 --> 00:04:33,810
with ease, with these four rules.

67
00:04:33,810 --> 00:04:34,810
1.

68
00:04:34,810 --> 00:04:39,379
An up bar starts an upswing and confirms the
end of a downswing.

69
00:04:39,379 --> 00:04:40,379
2.

70
00:04:40,379 --> 00:04:44,819
A down bar starts a downswing and confirms
the end of an upswing.

71
00:04:44,819 --> 00:04:45,819
3.

72
00:04:45,819 --> 00:04:49,860
Inside bars do not affect the direction of
the current swing because they do not break

73
00:04:49,860 --> 00:04:52,710
the previous high and low
4.

74
00:04:52,710 --> 00:04:57,639
Outside bars break both the previous high
and low so it introduces uncertainty into

75
00:04:57,639 --> 00:04:59,139
the market structure.

76
00:04:59,139 --> 00:05:05,060
However, as each swing is a minor trend itself
and trends tend to continue, we give the benefit

77
00:05:05,060 --> 00:05:07,270
of the doubt to the current swing.

78
00:05:07,270 --> 00:05:11,220
Thus, outside bars in an upswing continues
the upswing.

79
00:05:11,220 --> 00:05:16,020
Similarly, outside bars in a downswing continues
the downswing.

80
00:05:16,020 --> 00:05:22,400
Now, we took the previous example and we marked
out the market swings, based on the bars that

81
00:05:22,400 --> 00:05:25,230
changed the direction of the market swings.

82
00:05:25,230 --> 00:05:29,830
The circled bars are inside bars and outside
bars and they do not affect the direction

83
00:05:29,830 --> 00:05:32,740
of the market swings.

84
00:05:32,740 --> 00:05:36,480
So most swings are confirmed by an up bar
or a down bar.

85
00:05:36,480 --> 00:05:41,389
However, under exceptional circumstances,
it is possible for a swing to form without

86
00:05:41,389 --> 00:05:43,639
either an up bar or a down bar.

87
00:05:43,639 --> 00:05:48,349
An upswing can be formed when the market rises
above the last swing high without forming

88
00:05:48,349 --> 00:05:49,639
an up bar.

89
00:05:49,639 --> 00:05:54,740
Similarly, a downswing can be formed when
the market falls below the last swing low

90
00:05:54,740 --> 00:05:56,580
without forming a down bar.

91
00:05:56,580 --> 00:06:00,650
An outside bar is always involved in such
cases.

92
00:06:00,650 --> 00:06:05,659
This is example of the market forming a new
downswing without a down bar.

93
00:06:05,659 --> 00:06:10,990
And this is an example of the market forming
a new upswing without an up bar.

94
00:06:10,990 --> 00:06:11,990
1.

95
00:06:11,990 --> 00:06:15,069
The market has been forming regular swings
with up bars and down bars.

96
00:06:15,069 --> 00:06:16,069
2.

97
00:06:16,069 --> 00:06:19,100
This bullish outside bar broke above the last
swing high.

98
00:06:19,100 --> 00:06:20,570
There was no up bar.

99
00:06:20,570 --> 00:06:26,379
However, as the last swing high has been broken,
despite the lack of an up bar, we must recognise

100
00:06:26,379 --> 00:06:29,050
that a new upswing has been formed.

101
00:06:29,050 --> 00:06:32,610
And here is an outside bearish bar marking
a new swing.

102
00:06:32,610 --> 00:06:38,379
Let’s take a look at another price swing
example and see which shows the correct price

103
00:06:38,379 --> 00:06:39,379
swings?

104
00:06:39,379 --> 00:06:42,389
Is it A or B?

105
00:06:42,389 --> 00:06:43,970
Example B is the correct one.

106
00:06:43,970 --> 00:06:47,590
Although this point might seem like a swing
low, it is not.

107
00:06:47,590 --> 00:06:51,999
Typically, an outside bar doesn’t end or
start a price swing.

108
00:06:51,999 --> 00:06:57,330
Without a down bar or a break below the last
swing low, an upswing will continue.

109
00:06:57,330 --> 00:06:59,240
So why is this analysis important?

110
00:06:59,240 --> 00:07:03,770
Well, if you understand how the swings are
marked and you have learned to identify market

111
00:07:03,770 --> 00:07:08,320
swings clearly, you can confidently state
the current direction of the market wave at

112
00:07:08,320 --> 00:07:09,990
any point in time.

113
00:07:09,990 --> 00:07:14,669
This is an important first step to uncovering
the market bias.

114
00:07:14,669 --> 00:07:18,639
The next step to determine market bias is
determining swing pivots.

115
00:07:18,639 --> 00:07:22,580
Swing pivots are the turning points of each
market swing.

116
00:07:22,580 --> 00:07:26,200
The point where an upswing turns down is a
swing high.

117
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:29,229
The point where a downswing turns up is a
swing low.

118
00:07:29,229 --> 00:07:32,160
Why are swing pivots important?

119
00:07:32,160 --> 00:07:35,669
Swing pivots are price points that turned
the tide of the market.

120
00:07:35,669 --> 00:07:37,260
These points are not random.

121
00:07:37,260 --> 00:07:41,180
They represent a momentary change in demand
and supply forces.

122
00:07:41,180 --> 00:07:46,759
In this example, bulls could not move the
market above this swing high, not even for

123
00:07:46,759 --> 00:07:47,759
one tick.

124
00:07:47,759 --> 00:07:52,080
This means that at that point in time, no
one was willing to offer a price higher than

125
00:07:52,080 --> 00:07:53,550
the swing high.

126
00:07:53,550 --> 00:07:58,520
Traders saw no value above the swing high
and didn’t want to buy above the swing high.

127
00:07:58,520 --> 00:08:03,560
Hence, when prices move close to or above
a swing high, we must remember that traders

128
00:08:03,560 --> 00:08:06,319
saw no value in buying above that point previously.

129
00:08:06,319 --> 00:08:11,669
Assuming that most traders have not changed
their opinions, prices are unlikely to move

130
00:08:11,669 --> 00:08:13,030
above the swing high.

131
00:08:13,030 --> 00:08:18,050
So, the swing high marks a price area that
resists the market from moving up.

132
00:08:18,050 --> 00:08:20,289
This is what we call a resistance area.

133
00:08:20,289 --> 00:08:25,280
In the case of a swing low, the bears could
not push prices below it.

134
00:08:25,280 --> 00:08:29,849
This occurrence implies that no trader was
willing to sell below that particular price

135
00:08:29,849 --> 00:08:30,849
point.

136
00:08:30,849 --> 00:08:33,950
The reason was that traders perceived value
below the swing low.

137
00:08:33,950 --> 00:08:36,140
They want to buy value and not sell it.

138
00:08:36,140 --> 00:08:40,600
So when everyone wants to buy and no one wants
to sell, price goes up and we get a swing

139
00:08:40,600 --> 00:08:41,600
low.

140
00:08:41,600 --> 00:08:45,230
The logic we applied to analyzing swing highs
works for swing lows.

141
00:08:45,230 --> 00:08:50,470
When the market falls near a swing low, assuming
that traders still see value in buying below

142
00:08:50,470 --> 00:08:53,850
the swing low, prices are unlikely to fall
below it.

143
00:08:53,850 --> 00:08:58,590
The swing low supports the market and is a
support area.

144
00:08:58,590 --> 00:09:03,410
The failure of swing highs and lows to hold
up at resistance and support respectively

145
00:09:03,410 --> 00:09:05,630
leads us into another concept.

146
00:09:05,630 --> 00:09:11,190
• Failed resistance turns into support
• Failed support turns into resistance

147
00:09:11,190 --> 00:09:16,460
When a resistance level projected from a swing
high fails to block a market from rising higher,

148
00:09:16,460 --> 00:09:18,840
it turns into a support area.

149
00:09:18,840 --> 00:09:24,510
This is because, despite its failure, the
price point remains memorable to market participants.

150
00:09:24,510 --> 00:09:29,820
A price point that has failed decisively as
a resistance will then serve as a reliable

151
00:09:29,820 --> 00:09:30,820
support.

152
00:09:30,820 --> 00:09:33,530
You can apply the same logic to failed support.

153
00:09:33,530 --> 00:09:39,120
After failing to hold prices up, they serve
as potential resistance.

154
00:09:39,120 --> 00:09:41,390
`
Here we have an example of a failed resistance

155
00:09:41,390 --> 00:09:42,570
turning into support.

156
00:09:42,570 --> 00:09:43,570
1.

157
00:09:43,570 --> 00:09:46,500
We used swing highs to project possible resistance
levels.

158
00:09:46,500 --> 00:09:47,500
2.

159
00:09:47,500 --> 00:09:50,420
The market rose above with ease, crushing
the resistance.

160
00:09:50,420 --> 00:09:51,420
3.

161
00:09:51,420 --> 00:09:55,570
The failed resistance then became a powerful
support zone.

162
00:09:55,570 --> 00:09:58,450
In a nutshell, there are two key skills in
reading price action.

163
00:09:58,450 --> 00:09:59,450
1.

164
00:09:59,450 --> 00:10:02,610
Evaluate how likely a swing pivot will hold
up as support/resistance.

165
00:10:02,610 --> 00:10:03,610
2.

166
00:10:03,610 --> 00:10:09,770
Understand the implication of a swing pivot
not holding up as support/resistance.

167
00:10:09,770 --> 00:10:14,370
This might seem very easy and basic, but is
one of the most important concepts in trading.

168
00:10:14,370 --> 00:10:18,540
Tracking market swings and understanding what
they are telling you about the market are

169
00:10:18,540 --> 00:10:21,460
foundational price action trading skills.

170
00:10:21,460 --> 00:10:26,390
Many traders follow market swings in a wrong
manner and find them useful only in hindsight.

171
00:10:26,390 --> 00:10:30,290
They are unable to apply the concept of market
swings in real-time.

172
00:10:30,290 --> 00:10:34,681
With this simple approach, you will know exactly
the current price wave you are in, and with

173
00:10:34,681 --> 00:10:39,950
a solid understanding of support and resistance,
and confluence of swing pivots, you will find

174
00:10:39,950 --> 00:10:43,200
the best areas on a chart to trade from.

175
